<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="240" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[153,1038,516,760]" pageId="3" pageNumber="240">
<emphasis box="[153,261,619,642]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="240">Comments</emphasis>
: The specimens were collected around a manure pile. According to several authors, 
<taxonomicName box="[248,370,649,672]" class="Insecta" family="Sepsidae" genus="Meroplius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="240" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[248,370,649,672]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="240">M. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is especially attracted to human faeces (
<bibRefCitation author="Melander, A. L. &amp; Spuler, A." journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Agricultural Experimental Station Washington" pageId="3" pageNumber="240" pagination="1 - 103" part="143" refString="Melander, A. L. &amp; Spuler, A. 1917. The dipterous families Sepsidae and Piophilidae. - Bulletin of the Agricultural Experimental Station Washington 143: 1 - 103." title="The dipterous families Sepsidae and Piophilidae" type="journal article" year="1917">Melander &amp;Spuler 1917</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, A. C. &amp; Meier, R." box="[223,435,677,702]" journalOrPublisher="Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica" pageId="3" pageNumber="240" pagination="1 - 221" part="37" refString="Pont, A. C. &amp; Meier, R. 2002. The Sepsidae (Diptera) of Europe. - Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica 37: 1 - 221." title="The Sepsidae (Diptera) of Europe" type="journal article" year="2002">Pont &amp;Meier 2002</bibRefCitation>
). It has thus been argued that the observed population decline of this species may be linked to improved hygienic conditions in Central Europe (van der 
<bibRefCitation author="van der Goot, V. S." box="[333,451,736,760]" journalOrPublisher="Entomologist's Monthly Magazine" pageId="3" pageNumber="240" pagination="82" part="123" refString="van der Goot, V. S. 1987. Meroplius minutus (Wiedemann) (Dipt., Sepsidae) extinct in the Low Countries. - Entomologist's Monthly Magazine 123: 82." title="Meroplius minutus (Wiedemann) (Dipt., Sepsidae) extinct in the Low Countries" type="journal article" year="1987">Goot 1987</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
